token_lists.title: Transmogrified Interfaces
token_lists.description:
Ever get the feeling that life's a game with changing rules and no clear sides, one you are compelled to play yet cannot win? Welcome to gamespace. Gamespace is where and how we live today. It is everywhere and nowhere: the main chance, the best shot, the big leagues, the only game in town.

~~ McKenzie Wark, Gamer Theory

token_lists.title: Sprites
token_lists.description:
“…In partnership with the sprites, fae pilots would weave a way through time and space to connect far off destinations within seconds. Sprites were the magical conduits that allowed the fae to reach their far-flung destinations. Sprites could be in any form, from the most mundane to the most fantastical. Most of the sprites were small enough to fit in the palm of one hand, but some of them were as big as a small dog or even bigger.”
Read more - https://medium.com/@wicgan/sprites-1e8c2059a990

token_lists.title: Lighthouses
token_lists.description: “…Lighthouses were situated at key points across the interspaces and provided both guidance and shelter for weary travellers. …These ancient interstellar structures served as waypoints, guiding interspace travellers to safety and helping them navigate the twists and turns of the Lightstreams and offered a safe haven during their intergalactic travels.” https://medium.com/@wicgan/inter-dimensional-travel-817751db830a

token_lists.title: Vida de Plutón
token_lists.description:
"So you had a white heart inside your gray surface.
So you had high mountains of ice that braced you.
Who could stand your coldness?

But there you are,
in all your magnificence,
with your immense solitude,
enlightening us.
Dwarf."
 - Luz A. Santana (Vida de Plutón, 2018)

This image is part of Vida de Plutón (Life of Pluto), a photobook published by Pequeño Pato Salvaje in 2018. The book is an introspective journey that carries the reader through a universe of emotional sensations inspired by memory, doubt, and fear of life.

Just like the planet Pluto that was kept far away and forgotten for a long time until a space mission reached the planet and discovered its heart, Vida de Plutón (Life of Pluto) represents the author’s return to herself, to recover her heart.
